A Quick ABOUT ME;

Hi there Patrons! Here is a quick about me. Names Ethan Riddle, I am an artist/ innovator who wants to share my vision of the beauty in the world through the sculptures, fiber art, ceramics, wood-Carving, toys, machines and drawings that I create. My art is inspired by the people and places I know, and questions I have about the world around me, my life as a Type (1) diabetic and often times by my dreams inspire me. I strive to live a deep and simple life, and to find the beauty in every moment while I'm still here on Earth. I hope that by sharing my creations and my creative process with you, you too will see more beauty in the world around you. And push on! No matter what! Because life’s beautiful, but you can’t always see that on your own. We all need that little push to help us get going.

A little more about me...

My path to becoming an artist has been a long and indirect one. I can remember spending lots of time drawing as a kid. My favorite subjects then were guns, science, and space. My earliest equine drawings started as tracings of guns, and planets. As I got older, I shifted my focus to drawing people also places, and spent a lot of time copying photos from magazines and books, and drawing. When I was a teenager, my dad bought me a air brush kit, and I discovered my love of art. At that time, I enjoyed art as a hobby, but didn't see myself as an artist, so I chose to pursue my interest in science. I studied engineering as an undergraduate student, and other than one art history class and one sculpture class (which I loved!), art really wasn't on my radar.

became Type (1) Diabetic when I was 15 years old. And when faced with the realities of the cost of Healthcare as I grew older and not being able to work a steady job, my grandmother, family and I agreed that it would be best for me to stay at home with my disabilities. So i began my time as a full time at home artist and innovator. Three years later, I started to die, but after all the time and doctors they fixed me and changed my life. while I would love to say that being sick exposed me to the arts again, and that I suddenly found my artistic gifts, I spent more time cleaning up after my family' art projects than making any of my own. Being so sick did, however, cause me to reflect about my true interests, and while I found that I continued to like science, my heart was called back to the little wood, paintings, and sculptures that I did as a teenager.

I expressed my desire to start exploring art to my Grandmother, and she very thoughtfully helped me out with my medical bills, and a peaceful place to work. Which I used to make a relief portrait of Elvis Presley. That portrait awakened my desire to explore my artistic abilities, and so when my hope is to continue to learn more about art and to experiment with different media as I find my artistic voice.

Thanks for reading, and thank you for your support!
-As you may know, Patreon allows fans to contribute a small monthly tip to their favorite creators, and as you're here you must be a fan of my work to some degree!

Your patronage will help me to:

  1. Purchase art supplies, including but not limited to, clay, glazes, stains, armature supplies, drawing pencils, wood, paper, and more.
  2. Pay for kiln firing of ceramic pieces
  3. Pay fees for entries into art shows and fairs
  4. Fund continuing education so that I can improve my artistic skills
  5. Build a dedicated studio space
  6. Purchase a kiln of my very own
  7. Help pay for medical supplies, and hospital visits
    I hope that you enjoy the content that I share with you. Thank you for your patronage!

Each DIY project video I make requires a lot of time and effort. From coming up with the initial idea, to designing and building them whilst filming every step, to writing scripts, editing the videos, and then making sure that any project files and circuit diagrams are made and uploaded for certain projects. It all takes time, especially to keep the quality up! This does mean that I can't churn them out particularly quickly compared to other types of content, which can also hit the channel negatively due to the way YouTube's algorithm works. I'd like to keep making quality videos (no quick 'hacks' here!!!), so any contributions are greatly appreciated, and will genuinely allow me to make more content as I won't have to be so heavily reliant on sponsorships to fill the gap.
As I'd like everyone to receive equal rewards there's just one tier, which is $5 a month. Not only do you directly support the channel, but you also get:

$5 a month you’ll get

Free Gifts*
Free access to all upcoming PDF project guides
Sponsor-free versions of videos that might contain them
You can suggest project ideas if there is something specific you need - they will be considered for a future video
Free access to project resources (blueprints, SVG files, etc.
Access to the Patreon Private Feed
Exclusive behind the scenes content and updates

So with that, I'd like to give you a huge THANK YOU! Especially if you contribute here on Patreon. You guys really are a fantastic audience! Couldn't ask for better.
P.S. The PDF guides will be coming out later in the year, and will contain more detailed instructions, tips, and facts that might not have made it into the project video. Not every project will have a guide, only the ones that are complicated enough to warrant dedicated instructions (Like Slide Shows)
I get real pleasure from teaching the things I have learned from the people and processes I have run into in my Years... building and blacksmithing. However, with with most pleasurable pass-times... there is a cost.

Creating these videos, and projects competes directly with my ability to run my business, and ability to take care of my health and feed the family. I think you would be surprised...and disturbed, if you knew how many man-hours I’ve spend producing content.

This is a labor of love, but it IS labor, and the financial costs can't be ignored. There will come a day (I hope) when business will be fully self sufficient. However that day is not yet here - and I havea lot of work to do before it is.

Work has been proceeding in order to bring perfection to the crudely conceived idea of a machine that would not only supply inverse reactive current for use in unilateral phase detractors, but would also be capable of automatically synchronizing cardinal grammeters. Such a machine is the "Turbo-Encabulator."
The original machine had a base-plate of prefabulated amulite, surmounted by a malleable logarithmic casing in such a way that the two spurving bearings were in a direct line with the pentametric fan. The main winding was of the normal lotus-o-delta type placed in panendermic semi-boloid slots in the stator, every seventh conductor being connected by a nonreversible trem'e pipe to the differential girdlespring on the up end of the grammeters.

For anyone else using a Robo3d R1 plus+:
Extruder removal google searches (ex. to clear a jam) will often say "look for these two screws" - screws that don't exist on your model. Instead directly behind the "Do Not Touch" warning symbol sticker on the printer head there is a screw going vertically under the unit. LOOSEN this (do not need to remove) and you'll be able to swivel the silver clip on the top right hand side of the unit away, this will free the extruder head. Then pre-heat extruder to 220 and gently pull to remove filament jam. If you need I can send pictures of what I mean to you, just PM me.

Printing surface note:
On Robo3d R1 Plus + unit, printing on painters tape (frog tape in my case) works well and does not have to be changed between prints right away (most items will pop off very easily). HOWEVER, supports are too thin to have good purchase on the tape. Recommend if you are printing objects that need supports, best if you stick with glue stick method (har har).
